text: This is a presentation about how I got to contribute to CNCF projects I'm more than 50 years old so I never thought it would be something I could do at this age and I'd like to share that with you maybe inspire you to do the same So really quick I'll explain a little bit about my journey my learnings while starting my and share how you can contribute as well So people who know me one of the weirdest things about me is I grew up in a farmhouse with more than 40 cats and no electricity so that's a fun fact about me How a person like that ended up being an OpenTelemetry member I don't know but it happened So if it's happened it can happen to everyone I also as a fun fact I was at a dance boarding school when I was growing up That's maybe why I thought women can do engineering because all my teachers were women so math teacher chemistry everyone And my first coding class was when I was 10 years old and I went with my brother because of course he was the one studying coding but I liked it so I decided to go to university and get an engineering degree My work has been always on insurance and banking and we used open source but we never contributed to it so I never thought I would But like in 2018 I was lucky that I joined Elastic and then Grafana and this is where I actually get hey these companies contribute to open source we have open source projects so maybe it's possible to do that I started volunteering first as a community organiser with Software Crafters Barcelona but I also wanted to give back and for me contribute to open source was let's do some pull requests let's do something that's on GitHub and it's a contribution This year I started with open telemetry and I was very bold and said hey I'm going to go to the Kubernetes operator and just help with that But it didn't work very well for me I think it was better to start with something easier for me less technical probably and I decided because I had to read the open telemetry documentation why not translate into Spanish That's something that the team is doing It helps the documentation being accessible to everyone and it was easy to contribute I had found a great great community there especially Carol Valencia She immediately asked to have a meeting with me and we connected so she's helped me a lot She shared with me some instructions very detailed on how to do my first contribution and that helped me a lot I felt very confident that I could do it and I could always ask her to help me with any questions Just a month after that this team they actually offered me to become a member I didn't expect that and they reached out to me and said hey you're doing great I was doing just one pull request every week small pull request I tried to follow their instructions not do big pull requests just small things learn from them and iterate That's how I became a member but thanks to them because they are great sponsors But I realized I was already contributing to OpenTelemetry to the community because I was already organizing events learnings here is join the right project for you listen to contributors read the contributions be realistic be consistent they will appreciate that There's all sorts of contributions not just organizing a conference it's contributing to open source If you can work for a company that supports OSF that's great and remember to have fun How you can contribute This is I will leave the slides for you but this is important There's technical contributions and there's non code contributions so like project documentation is one of those You don't have to actually contribute to one of the 200 projects technically you can but you don't have to it's a good contribution as well If you want to join the cloud native community these are the different ways you can I do the mentorship program if you feel like you're not ready there is a mentorship program it's meant for everyone even if you're 50 that's good Where is help needed There is this URL that's very useful if you don't know it you can find issues that are looking for help There is a label with first time issues so that's the one you can actually take to contribute Another thing that's happening this month of October is the October 1st it's a good way to contribute and there is a resources for beginners that's actually very good as well And takeaways from this talk it's never too late or too early to contribute Find a project you like because then it's when you stick to it Not all contributions are cold there's all types of contributions start small be realistic be consistent seek companies who support OSS if you can and don't wait start and have fun And for you to take away if you're I don't know who has not yet contributed to open source here
